post_text:
"It's Friday! Every normal Friday at THS we sing the "Tonasket Fight Song" on the rail (commons, stairs, and upstairs railing). We talk about our successes of the week and we come together as a high school. Our band and cheerleaders perform, and we all join in and sing Loud and Proud!
This is an audience participation activity. Sing along and at the end of the song Yell the words. We may not all be together in person, but from a distance, we are all STRONGER TOGETHER!!
Happy Friday! It's Great To Be A Tonasket Tiger! Go Tigers!!!! :)
Push open and play! And sing it Loud and Proud! Have a GREAT DAY!" ~ Anita Asmussen, HS ASB Advisor

Special Thanks to Mr. Stiles THS/TMS band director for playing and recording the fight song and Diego Laguna 21st Century MS-HS Site Director for his awesome computer program skills.

THS Positivity Project!
shared_text:
Tonasket School District
December 23, 2019 at 2:57 PM ¬∑

Get your tissues, this has all the feels... We cannot love this enough, watching their faces is the best gift. Watch till the end you won't be disappointed.
"This video is the Tonasket High School Positivity Project. We love our students, and there are so many we could have selected to complete this project!! Many teachers struggled with only choosing one or two students. Even with that said, this video is just over twenty minutes long--could have easily been hours. That says so much about what a great place THS is to be!!! We thank our students for inspiring us and being our WHY behind this work!
HUGE kudos and thanks to Diego Laguna, Abigail Steinshouer and Madeline Ashmore for creating this video!!!" ~ Trisha Roach, HS Principal

With the emergency closing of school on September 8, 2020, because of the effects of the fires on phone and internet services, we used our snow day that was scheduled into the calendar on March 15. To avoid confusion about whether or not March 15 is a school day, the school calendar has been revised to reflect the changes of those two dates. The changes you will see are:

1. September 8, 2020 - no school - emergency closure
2. March 15, 2020 - is marked as a regular school day

The first quarter now has 42 days, and the third quarter has 47 days, still keeping our school year at a total of 180 days.

The revised school calendar is attached.

post_text:
9/11 Remembrance
Today is the 19th anniversary of the terrorist attacks against our nation that took down the Twin Towers, hit the Pentagon, and resulted in the crashing of Flight 93. For my generation, it is one of those events that has defined much of our lives. It is also a great time to remember the sacrifice of all of the first responders who ran towards the danger 19 years ago and continue to do so in our nation and in our community as the past few weeks have so dramatically shown us with the horrific wildfires. Be safe, give your loved ones an extra hug today, and take some time to remember the great things about our nation and community that come out in times of crisis.

post_text: Thank you PUD!
shared_text:
Public Utility District #1 of Okanogan County
September 9 at 8:18 AM ¬∑

UPDATE 10:13 a.m.: As always, services are up and down and spotty at best in certain areas of the county. Just know that we are continuing to work with our partners to get everyone back online and on the phone. Thanks for your patience!

ORIGINAL POST 8:15 a.m.: Just this morning, we successfully rerouted CenturyLink traffic and their service should be back up in the county! That means cell service should be finally getting some bars where it's been gone the last couple days. Our awesome broadband crew will continue to work to get us all connected! And in case you missed it yesterday, you can connect to any of our free, open internet access drive-in WiFi hotspots throughout the county.

UPDATE the timeline has been extended until September 11‚ÄºÔ∏è
FYI Applications for the Pandemic-EBT must be completed by August 31, 2020:
Because COVID-19 closed our school facilities, your child(ren) is eligible for food assistance, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT): Emergency School Meals Program.
P-EBT provides families with funds to make up for the cost of meals while school was closed. This benefit is for Washington children in grades K-12. These benefits will be on an Electronic Benefits Transfer (EBT) card, which is used like a debit card to buy groceries.
Tonasket School District provides all meals free to all our students through the Community Eligibility Program (CEP), so your student(s) is eligible for the P-EBT benefit.

post_text: Our community showed up in a big way! We üíõüíô Tonasket!
shared_text:
Tonasket High School ASB
June 8 at 5:23 PM ¬∑

HUGE kudos to the Tonasket community for loving our seniors!! We had our first ever senior celebration parade on June 6, 2020 at 3 p.m., the time the seniors would have graduated.

Big thanks to the Tonasket Fire Department, City of Tonasket, WA DOT, WSP, and Okanogan County Sheriff's Office for supporting this event.

Convertibles, antique rigs, pick-ups, cars, ATVS, and even an ice cream truck rolled through the town to present our Tigers :)

We cannot wait to see everyone at our graduation ceremony on July 11, 2020 at the football field.

Beyond humbled,
Principal Roach

P.S. Thank you to Diego Laguna for this drone footage.

OCCAC (Okanogan County Community Action Council) is encouraging individuals and families to utilize the food pantry closest to where they live. Please see the pictures for the locations and times.
The Okanogan County Community Action flier outlines assistance available to individuals and families who live in Okanogan County. Families who need assistance are encouraged to reach out to Okanogan County Community Action. The best way is by phone at 509-422-4041 or toll-free 877-641-0101.

shared_text:
Tonasket Athletic Booster Club
June 3 at 10:52 AM ¬∑

Senior Spring Sport Athlete: Heidi Cruz

Spring Sport: Track and Field

Event: 4x1, 200M, Long Jump

Favorite thing about Track and Field: The ability to work independently and focus on your weaknesses to improve in each event but still being able to reward the team and yourself if you reach your goal.

Goal for Senior Season: To go to state in 3 events

What does playing a sport at THS mean to you: It means that I can demonstrate my support to represent our community by being hardworking and showing my passion for sports.

Any words of advice for your under class teammates? Nothing worth having comes easy and never hold yourself above anyone else. Always try to be your own strongest motivator when you feel like giving up and use that mentality to lift others who need a leader.

Funny Spring Sports Story you want to share from your years at THS: Finding a photo of myself after our cashmere meet, passed out, clutching a half eaten subway sandwich in my hands.

üêØüíôüíõüêØüíôüíõüêØüíôüíõ We are proud of you Heidi!!

Senior Spring Sport Athlete: Cody Clark

Spring Sport: Tennis

Position: Singles and Doubles

Favorite thing about Tennis: How easy it is to enjoy practices, and how quickly the game flows.

Goal for Senior Season: I wanted to make it past districts.

What does playing a sport at THS mean to you: Playing a sport for Tonasket is a great way to challenge yourself in competition while being surrounded by your friends.

Any words of advice for your under class teammates? Don‚Äôt quit now because it‚Äôs too hard because your time will come.

A Favorite Tennis memory: One time at practice our assistant coach Brad found a flat tennis ball so he hit it as hard as he could up into the air and somehow hit a bird off of a telephone pole. The bird survived but the entire team went crazy over Brad‚Äôs amazing show of his talent.

üêØüíôüíõüêØüíôüíõüêØüíôüíõ We are proud of you Cody!!

shared_text:
Tonasket Athletic Booster Club
May 28 at 10:38 AM ¬∑

Senior Spring Sport Athlete: Austin Cox

Spring Sport: Baseball

Postion: Outfield

Favorite thing about Baseball: I love how the whole team comes together to make the play. Even if one person wasn't out their in their position, we wouldn't be able to make the play.

Goal for Senior Season: My goal was to do the best that I could. And just have a fun season for my senior year.

What does playing a sport at THS mean to you: It means that no matter what, we always build each other up. Even if someone messed up the play, we always build them up. If someone gets hurt, we are always their to help them. THS sports, we always work as a team.

Any words of advice for your under class teammates? If you are going to do a sport, even just for fun, try your hardest. You will learn that you can do a lot more than you think you can. Never give up!

üíôüíõüêØüíôüíõ We are proud of you Austin!!!

If you turned in a graduation photo, baby photo and quote to the yearbook, we have those. If you did not turn in these items, please submit them along with your cap and gown photo.

shared_text:
KHQ.COM
Nationwide campaign lights up football fields to show support for the class of 2020

Tonasket Athletic Booster Club
April 9 at 8:13 PM ¬∑

A message from Principal Roach!!

HELLO!!!!

We are participating in a NATIONWIDE campaign to celebrate and honor our SENIORS and their academic and extracurricular accomplishments!!

https://www.khq.com/coronavirus/nationwide-campaign-lights-up-football-fields-to-show-support-for-the-class-of-2020/article_1c41f6c4-7aad-11ea-833d-3f15e74d3244.html?fbclid=IwAR1KjXL88KoUfkP8nhY-GYRjVp_8bWDQpVk2n9ekjt01aAy4ZP7h7HllYgc

On Friday, April 10th (that's tomorrow), we will be turning on the football field lights at 8:20 p.m. for twenty minutes. Why 8:20? That represents 2020 in military time! This is one way to show our support for the Class of 2020.

Students and community members CANNOT come to the football field because we are not allowed to assemble in any size group at this time. If you drive by to see this event, please remember to practice physical distancing. Be safe!

As well, Diego has agreed to use the drone to video this, and we will post a video on our school FB next week for those who may not be able to witness it in person.

Together we are stronger!

Much love,
Principal Roach

shared_text:
OKANOGANTRANSIT.COM
Okanogan County Transit Authority

Okanogan County Transit Authority
March 28 at 1:14 PM ¬∑

ATTENTION - Suspending Service

In order to ensure that we can provide the needed protection to staff and the public, TranGO will be suspending regular service on all bus routes on Monday, March 30 and Tuesday, March 31. We are also committed to providing the essential service to those who are required to work. If you are a worker who needs a ride to work, please call our office at (509) 557-6177 so arrangements can be made for the next few days.
We are awaiting supplies so we can ensure the buses are cleaned and sanitized to help prevent the spread of COVID 19.

We are committed to the communities in our county while keeping everyone safe. TranGO is currently working on plans to help provide bus service for essential trips during the next few weeks. Check out our website at www.okanogantransit.com and our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/okanogantransitauthority for updates as we move forward. We apologize for any inconvenience to our riders. Stay home and stay safe!

If you are a worker who needs a ride to work, please call our office at (509) 557-6177 so arrangements can be made for the next few days.
We are awaiting supplies so we can ensure the buses are cleaned and sanitized to help prevent the spread of COVID 19.

We are committed to the communities in our county while keeping everyone safe. TranGO is currently working on plans to help provide bus service for essential trips during the next few weeks. Check out our website at www.okanogantransit.com and our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/okanogantransitauthority for updates as we move forward. We apologize for any inconvenience to our riders. Stay home and stay safe!

post_text:
During the closure of schools in our area, we are offering supervised childcare for school-age Tonasket students in grades K-5 for children of healthcare workers and first responders who are affected by the school closure. Our program will operate at Tonasket Elementary School on weekdays until schools across Washington State reopen or until June 9, 2020, whichever is first.

We will begin providing care on Tuesday, March 24th at Tonasket Elementary School.
Childcare hours are from 8:30 AM to 3:30 PM, Monday through Friday.

The childcare we offer is NOT intended to be a full instructional program, but a supervised environment with enrichment and outdoor physical activities monitored by members of our staff.

Parents are responsible for transportation to and from Tonasket Elementary School and ensuring that their child is in good health. Foodservice will include breakfast and lunch daily at no charge.

If you have any questions, please contact Lilly Martin at (509) 486-4933 ext 5308 or lmartin@tonasket.wednet.edu

Many of you watched or have heard about Governor Jay Inslee‚Äôs press release on COVID-19, and his proclamation aimed at slowing the spread of COVID-19.

"Chelan-Douglas Health District, Grant County Health District, and Okanogan County Public Health are urging and recommending residents of our counties voluntarily follow Governor Inslee‚Äôs proclamation and reduce large gatherings." - March 11, 2020, OCPH Press Release

Click the link below to Okanogan County Health to read the full press release and Governor's proclamation.

Okanogan County Public Health

At this time TSD is canceling indoor gatherings that meet this criteria and we are in the process of determining any school events that fall into this category so that the proper notifications can be made.

We will follow up with more detailed information tomorrow.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we navigate this unprecedented period of time.

Sincerely,
Steve McCullough
Superintendent, Tonasket School District

Dear Tonasket Community,

While the Coronavirus (COVID 19) is not currently a US emergency or high risk in NCW, there is a lot of information circulating. We would like to share with you reliable resources to help keep you informed.

Reports on the status and responses to COVID-19 change daily. The WA State DOH (Department of Health), Centers for Disease Control (CDC), and the World Health Organization (WHO) are your best resources.

Local and State Health Departments would provide guidance on how to handle an outbreak if one was to happen in our area. WA is still considered a low risk area per DOH.

As with this and any other illness, the best thing to do is to wash hands often, stay home when you are sick and clean surfaces regularly. ~ Steve McCullough, Superintendent

For more information

https://www.doh.wa.gov/emergencies/coronavirus
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html

post_text: Congratulations Tiger Wrestlers! ON TO STATE üíôüíõüêÖ
shared_text:
Tonasket Tiger Wrestling
February 16 at 9:12 AM ¬∑

A great regional tournament for the boys yesterday qualifying 16 wrestlers for state and one alternate. We also came away with the team championship at 360 points, 2nd Lake Roosevelt 153, 3rd Kittitas 124...
Individual champions include Waylon Thomas, Waylon Wilson, Kevin Sanabria, Colin Silverthorn, Enrique Long, Austin Brock, and Carson Sasse. Coming in 2nd were, Laz Soria, Lane Bolich, Rielan Bretz, Carsen Walton, and Granger Sutton. Taking 3rd were Angel Depaz, Chris Rodriguez, Ryden Zabreznik, and Jesus Najara. Miguel Alavarez came in 4th for the alternate spot. Others who competed were Derrek Hollister, Curtis Willson, Blaize Wallis, Scott Kuntz, Evan Vanatta, Anthony Salazar, and Carlos Nicholas.
We're looking forward to next weekend in the Tacoma Dome. We have some things to fine tune, then we'll go over there and leave it all on the mat. Thank you to the awesome crowd who came and cheered on the boys yesterday, that means a lot to all of us.

post_text:
What is funded by an Educational Programs and Operation Levy?

The Replacement Educational Programs and Operation Levy will be used to maintain current programs and fund what the state does not consider ‚ÄúBasic Education‚Äù. Many programs we offer and the community expects are not technically considered ‚ÄúBasic Education‚Äù by the state of Washington. Our levies have supported and will continue to support the following:

Co-Curricular and Extracurricular ‚Äì drama, FFA, FBLA, knowledge bowl, athletics, cheerleading, etc.

Special Programs ‚Äì field trips, para-educators, administration, teaching staff in art, music, PE, electives and counseling.

Building and Grounds ‚Äì custodial, maintenance, and grounds personnel; materials and supplies; energy costs.

Curriculum and Technology ‚Äì curriculum materials (i.e. ELA and Math adoption), technology and devices for staff and students, technology staffing.
Link to our FAQ's page:
http://www.tonasket.wednet.edu/2020_levy

post_text: Great job Tiger Wrestlers!
shared_text:
Tonasket Tiger Wrestling
February 2 at 10:39 AM ¬∑

Boys and Girls had a good local tournament held in Okanogan to end our regular season on. Tonasket came out on top with a score of 247, Cascade with 160.5, Eastmont 158...
Individuals taking 1st were Cailee Denison, Waylon Thomas, Lane Bolich, Kevin Sanabria, Colin Silverthorn, and Carson Sasse. Coming in 2nd were Angel Depaz, Chris Rodriguez. Taking 3rd were Daniel Depaz, Lazaro Soria, Derrek Hollister, Waylon Wilson, Rielan Bretz, Blaize Wallis, Ryden Zabreznik, Jamie Wilson, and Gabriela Tellez. Others who wrestled were Yessica Soriano, Miguel Alvarez, Gerardo Martinez, Heriberto Martinez, Ameron Bretz, Everett Peterson, Logan Brock, Scott Kuntz, Anthony Salazar, Granger Sutton, and Carlos Nicolas.
Nice job and good luck as we go into the post season.
